<div class="noprint tright portal" style="border:solid #aaa 1px;margin:0.5em 0 0.5em 0.5em;">
<table style="background:#f9f9f9; font-size:85%; line-height:110%;">
<tr>
<td><a href="/wiki/File:Portal.svg" class="image" title="Portal.svg"><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c9/Portal.svg/28px-Portal.svg.png" width="28" height="28" border="0" /></a></td>
<td style="padding:0 0.2em;"><i><b><a href="/wiki/Portal:Judaism" title="Portal:Judaism">Judaism portal</a></b></i></td>
</tr>
</table>
</div>
<p>The <b>Talmud</b> (<a href="/wiki/Hebrew_language" title="Hebrew language">Hebrew</a>: <span lang="he" xml:lang="he">תַּלְמוּד</span> <i><span lang="he-Latn" xml:lang="he-Latn">talmūd</span></i> "instruction, learning", from a <a href="/wiki/Semitic_root" title="Semitic root">root</a> <i><span lang="he-Latn" xml:lang="he-Latn"><a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%D7%9C%D7%9E%D7%93" class="extiw" title="wikt:למד">lmd</a></span></i> "teach, study") is a record of <a href="/wiki/Rabbi" title="Rabbi">rabbinic</a> discussions pertaining to <a href="/wiki/Halakha" title="Halakha">Jewish law</a>, <a href="/wiki/Jewish_ethics" title="Jewish ethics">ethics</a>, customs, and history. It is a central text of mainstream <a href="/wiki/Judaism" title="Judaism">Judaism</a>.</p>
<p>The Talmud has two components: the <a href="/wiki/Mishnah" title="Mishnah">Mishnah</a> (c. 200 <a href="/wiki/Common_Era" title="Common Era">CE</a>), the first written compendium of Judaism's Oral Law; and the <a href="/wiki/Gemara" title="Gemara">Gemara</a> (c. 500 CE), a discussion of the Mishnah and related <a href="/wiki/Tannaim" title="Tannaim">Tannaitic</a> writings that often ventures onto other subjects and expounds broadly on the <a href="/wiki/Tanakh" title="Tanakh">Tanakh</a>.</p>
<p>The terms <i>Talmud</i> and <i>Gemara</i> are often used interchangeably. The Gemara is the basis for all codes of <a href="/wiki/Halakha" title="Halakha">rabbinic law</a> and is much quoted in other <a href="/wiki/Rabbinic_literature" title="Rabbinic literature">rabbinic literature</a>. The whole Talmud is also traditionally referred to as <i><b><span lang="he-Latn" xml:lang="he-Latn">Shas</span></b></i> (<span lang="he" xml:lang="he">ש"ס</span>), a <a href="/wiki/Hebrew_language" title="Hebrew language">Hebrew</a> abbreviation of <i><span lang="he-Latn" xml:lang="he-Latn">shisha sedarim</span></i>, the "six orders" of the Mishnah.</p>
