<li id="cite_note-6"><b><a href="#cite_ref-6" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="book" id="CITEREFAngel_S.C3.A1enz-Badillos1993">Angel Sáenz-Badillos (1993). <i>A History of the Hebrew Language</i>. Tr. John Elwolde. Cambridge: Cambridge University Press.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=A+History+of+the+Hebrew+Language&amp;rft.aulast=Angel+S%C3%A1enz-Badillos&amp;rft.au=Angel+S%C3%A1enz-Badillos&amp;rft.date=1993&amp;rft.pub=Tr.+John+Elwolde.+Cambridge%3A+Cambridge+University+Press&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Talmud"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-7"><b><a href="#cite_ref-7" title="">^</a></b> For a list see Ephraim Urbach, s.v. "Tosafot," in <i>Encyclopedia of Religion</i>.</li>
<li id="cite_note-8"><b><a href="#cite_ref-8" title="">^</a></b> See, <i>Pilpul</i>, Mordechai Breuer, in <i>Encyclopedia Judaica, Vol. 16, 2nd Ed (2007), Macmillan Reference, USA.</i></li>
<li id="cite_note-9"><b><a href="#cite_ref-9" title="">^</a></b> <i>Kol Melechet Higgayon</i>, the Hebrew translation of Averroes' epitome of Aristotle's logical works, was widely studied in northern Italy, particularly <a href="/wiki/Padua" title="Padua">Padua</a>.</li>
<li id="cite_note-10"><b><a href="#cite_ref-10" title="">^</a></b> On Pilpul, see <i>Pilpul</i>, Mordechai Breuer, Encyclopedia Judaica and H.H. Ben Sasson, <i>A History of the Jewish People</i>, p. 627, 717.</li>
<li id="cite_note-11"><b><a href="#cite_ref-11" title="">^</a></b> As Yonah Fraenkel shows in his book <i>Darko Shel Rashi be-Ferusho la-Talmud ha-Bavli</i>, one of <a href="/wiki/Rashi" title="Rashi">Rashi</a>'s major accomplishments was textual emendation. Rabbenu Tam, Rashi's grandson and one of the central figures in the Tosafist academies, polemicizes against textual emendation in his less studied work <i>Sefer ha-Yashar</i>. However, the Tosafists, too, emended the Talmudic text (See e.g. <i>Baba Kamma</i> 83b <i>s.v.</i> <i>af haka'ah ha'amurah</i> or <i>Gittin</i> 32a <i>s.v. mevutelet</i>) as did many other medieval commentators (see e.g. R. Shlomo ben Aderet, <i>Hidushei ha-Rashb"a al ha-Sha"s</i> to <i>Baba Kamma</i> 83b, or Rabbenu Nissim's commentary to Alfasi on <i>Gittin</i> 32a).</li>
<li id="cite_note-12"><b><a href="#cite_ref-12" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="book" id="CITEREFEtkes2002">Etkes, Immanuel (2002). <i>The Gaon of Vilna</i>. University of California Press. p.&#160;16. <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/0520223942" class="internal">ISBN 0520223942</a>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=The+Gaon+of+Vilna&amp;rft.aulast=Etkes&amp;rft.aufirst=Immanuel&amp;rft.au=Etkes%2C+Immanuel&amp;rft.date=2002&amp;rft.pages=p.%26nbsp%3B16&amp;rft.pub=University+of+California+Press&amp;rft.isbn=0520223942&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Talmud"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-13"><b><a href="#cite_ref-13" title="">^</a></b> Solomon Schechter, <i>Studies in Judaism</i> p.92.</li>
<li id="cite_note-14"><b><a href="#cite_ref-14" title="">^</a></b> <a href="/wiki/Hyam_Maccoby" title="Hyam Maccoby">Hyam Maccoby</a>, <i>Judaism on Trial</i>.</li>
<li id="cite_note-15"><b><a href="#cite_ref-15" title="">^</a></b> <a href="/wiki/Hyam_Maccoby" title="Hyam Maccoby">Hyam Maccoby</a>, op. cit.</li>
<li id="cite_note-16"><b><a href="#cite_ref-16" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="news" id="CITEREFJones1999">Jones, Jeremy (1999). "Talmudic Terrors". Australia/Israel Review.  "If any reader doubts the maliciousness, virulence and prevalence of such material in cyber-space, it is well worth a visit to the Internet site known as Talmud Expose (www.geocities.com/Athens/Cyprus/8815), in which Melbourne's David Maddison has performed the Herculean task of responding, one by one, to the hundreds of "anti-Talmud" quotes, lies and themes he has encountered on the Internet."</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.btitle=Talmudic+Terrors&amp;rft.atitle=&amp;rft.aulast=Jones&amp;rft.aufirst=Jeremy&amp;rft.au=Jones%2C+Jeremy&amp;rft.date=1999&amp;rft.pub=Australia%2FIsrael+Review&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Talmud"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
</ol>
</div>
